THOUGHT: The miscompilation shows SLP vectorizer forming a <2 x i16> compare when original scalar compare was on i32 after zext/sext. It inserts an i16 lane with 0 in the second element and compares as i16, changing signedness and result. The fix should ensure SLP does not vectorize compares across lanes when operands require different extend kinds or when the compare must be performed in the extended wider type. I will inspect and modify the logic that checks compatibility of compare ops to additionally require same operand types (post-extends) and avoid building vectors of the narrower element type for compares. Then I will run submit-patch to validate.

```bash
applypatch << 'EOF'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
@@
 static bool areCompatibleCmpOps(Value *BaseOp0, Value *BaseOp1, Value *Op0,
                                 Value *Op1, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
+  // Ensure we don't combine compares with mismatched operand types, especially
+  // when the original scalars were extended (sext/zext) to a wider type before
+  // the compare. Forming a vector compare over the narrower element type (e.g.
+  // i16) changes the semantics and can miscompile signed/unsigned relations.
+  // If operand types differ, require a bitcast-free equal type to proceed.
+  auto *Ty0 = Op0->getType();
+  auto *Ty1 = Op1->getType();
+  auto *BTy0 = BaseOp0 ? BaseOp0->getType() : nullptr;
+  auto *BTy1 = BaseOp1 ? BaseOp1->getType() : nullptr;
+  // If both base operands exist, check that types match pairwise.
+  if ((BTy0 && BTy1) &&
+      (!Ty0->isFirstClassType() || !Ty1->isFirstClassType() ||
+       (!Ty0->isIntegerTy() && !Ty0->isPointerTy()) ||
+       (!Ty1->isIntegerTy() && !Ty1->isPointerTy()) ||
+       Ty0 != BTy0 || Ty1 != BTy1)) {
+    return false;
+  }
   // TODO: It should be replaced with more precise check using
   // TargetLibraryInfo::getLibFunc and analysis if we can have
   // one vector compare for the given pairs of operands.
   // Currently, if the operation is commutative, we allow it by
   // default.
*** End Patch
EOF
 && submit-patch
```

